## Common Questions

**Q: Can I get a personal loan if I'm self-employed?**

Yes, but you'll need at least 2 years of business accounts. Approval rates are lower and interest slightly higher than salaried employees.

**Q: How does my credit score affect my rate?**

Big time. A CCRIS score of 1-2 (excellent) can save you 2-3% on interest. A score of 5-6 (poor) might disqualify you or push rates above 15%.

**Q: Should I use a personal loan to pay off credit card debt?**

Usually yes — IF you can get a rate below your credit card's 15-18% p.a. and you won't rack up new card debt.

**Q: Can I apply for multiple loans to compare offers?**

Not recommended. Each application shows up on CCRIS and too many inquiries hurt your score. Do your research first, then apply to your top 1-2 choices.

**Q: What if I get rejected?**

Wait 3-6 months before reapplying. Use that time to improve your credit score, pay down existing debt, or increase your income documentation.

## The Bottom Line

Comparing personal loans isn't about finding the flashiest ad or the bank your friend uses. It's about:

1. **Understanding your real needs** (how much, how fast, how long?)
2. **Knowing your qualification level** (income, credit score, employment type)
3. **Comparing the total cost** (EIR, not just advertised rate)
4. **Reading the fine print** (fees, penalties, flexibility)

The 20 minutes you spend comparing options now could save you thousands over the loan tenure.

